author: @pdpbasak
text: Hi Krish, just a little correction, in this video and even in your previous video you said that p-value and the significance value are the same and are denoted by alpha. Actually they are not the same. Significance value/level (alpha) is defined as the probability of rejecting the null hypothesis if it is true. Also known as the false positive (FP) rate. In contrast, p-value is defined as "the smallest" level of significance at which we can "still" reject the null hypothesis. For a particular test with a particular level of significance (alpha), p-value obtained can be greater, lesser or even equal to the alpha. The decision rule is to "reject" the null hypothesis if p-value < alpha.
